    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "text": "Each square on the chart is one stitch. Each symbol tells you which colour. Empty squares stay unworked.",
          "type": "text"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "attrs": {
        "level": 2
      },
      "content": [
        {
          "text": "Working the chart",
          "type": "text"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "orderedList",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "listItem",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": [
                {
                  "text": "Find your centre. ",
                  "type": "text",
                  "marks": [
                    {
                      "type": "bold"
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "text": "Fold the cloth in half lengthwise and again widthwise, and crease the centre lightly. Match this point to the centre of the chart, marked with a small arrow on each edge.",
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "listItem",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": [
                {
                  "text": "Mount in the hoop. ",
                  "type": "text",
                  "marks": [
                    {
                      "type": "bold"
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "text": "Stretch the cloth taut. the weave should bounce slightly when you tap it. Loosen the screw, lay the inner ring under, drop the outer ring over, work the cloth flat, then tighten the screw.",
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "listItem",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": [
                {
                  "text": "Start a thread. ",
                  "type": "text",
                  "marks": [
                    {
                      "type": "bold"
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "text": "Cut a 50 cm length of ",
                  "type": "text"
                },
                {
                  "text": "stranded cotton",
                  "type": "text",
                  "marks": [
                    {
                      "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                      "attrs": {
                        "termId": "cmpb7qm7c0001g4v4aunk3fu1"
                      }
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "text": ", separate two strands, and thread the needle. Use a ",
                  "type": "text"
                },
                {
                  "text": "loop start",
                  "type": "text",
                  "marks": [
                    {
                      "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                      "attrs": {
                        "termId": "cmpb7qm830002g4v45nmy7re5"
                      }
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "text": ". bring the needle up from the back with the loop tail still beneath the cloth, then on the first stitch pass the needle through the loop to anchor it.",
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "listItem",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": [
                {
                  "text": "Work each X. ",
                  "type": "text",
                  "marks": [
                    {
                      "type": "bold"
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "text": "From the back, bring the needle up at the bottom-left of a square. Take it down at the top-right of the same square. Bring it up again at the bottom-right and down at the top-left. That's one cross-stitch.",
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "listItem",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": [
                {
                  "text": "Work in rows. ",
                  "type": "text",
                  "marks": [
                    {
                      "type": "bold"
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "text": "Stitch each row of half-crosses from left to right (the /// legs), then come back right to left completing the X (the \\\\\\ legs). Working in passes keeps the top legs all leaning the same way, which is what gives finished cross-stitch its even look.",
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "listItem",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": [
                {
                  "text": "End a thread. ",
                  "type": "text",
                  "marks": [
                    {
                      "type": "bold"
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "text": "When about 8 cm of thread remains, pass the needle under the last four or five stitches on the back of the cloth and snip close. No knots.",
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "listItem",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": [
                {
                  "text": "Move to the next colour. ",
                  "type": "text",
                  "marks": [
                    {
                      "type": "bold"
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "text": "Rest the working needle in a margin of the cloth and start the next colour from a fresh thread. Don't carry thread more than three squares behind the work. it shows through pale cloth.",
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "attrs": {
        "level": 2
      },
      "content": [
        {
          "text": "Finishing",
          "type": "text"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "text": "When all the letters are worked, press the back of the cloth with a warm iron over a folded towel. Mount in a frame or stitch into a small cushion front.",
          "type": "text"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "attrs": {
        "level": 2
      },
      "content": [
        {
          "text": "If the stitching goes sideways",
          "type": "text"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "troubleshooter",
      "attrs": {
        "intro": "Five things that usually go wrong on a first cross-stitch and how to spot them.",
        "items": [
          {
            "fix": "Pick a single direction for the top legs (the convention is south-west to north-east, but consistency matters more than the specific direction) and check every stitch matches as you go. If the inconsistency is small, pick out the offending crosses with the eye of a second needle and re-stitch. If it's widespread, the piece is the practice piece you needed; start over and the next one will be clean.",
            "cause": "One row was worked left-to-right and the next right-to-left without flipping the top-leg direction, OR cross-stitches were worked individually with inconsistent top-leg direction.",
            "symptom": "Cross-stitch tops are running different directions — the finished piece looks scrappy from across the room"
          },
          {
            "fix": "Let the needle dangle every dozen stitches so the thread untwists. If the puckering is mild, a careful steam-press at the finishing stage will pull most of it out. If severe, the cloth wasn't held taut enough in the hoop — tighten the hoop's screw and re-tension the cloth between repositions.",
            "cause": "Thread tension built up as the needle was rolled the same way through each stitch.",
            "symptom": "Stitches are getting tighter as the work progresses — the cloth puckers around the design"
          },
          {
            "fix": "Frog (unpick) back to the closest correct ten-stitch grid line, re-check against the chart's bold rules, and restart from the corrected position. Working in ten-stitch blocks and pausing to count against the chart's bold rules at each block stops the error from accumulating further.",
            "cause": "A cumulative count error from too long a stretch without referencing the chart's bold-rule grid.",
            "symptom": "A miscounted block sits one row higher or one square left of where it should"
          },
          {
            "fix": "If the piece is early, pick out the offending start and use the away-knot or loop-start method instead. If it's late, leave the knot where it is and learn for the next piece — knots on the back are an aesthetic issue more than a structural one, and the finished piece will still look fine once mounted.",
            "cause": "Thread was started with a knot on the back rather than a loop start or away knot.",
            "symptom": "Knots are showing through the front of the cloth as bumps"
          },
          {
            "fix": "Pull the cloth taut in all directions while tightening the screw incrementally; the cloth should feel drum-tight, not sponge-soft. Reposition the hoop and re-tension every 30-45 minutes of stitching to prevent slippage.",
            "cause": "Hoop tension is too loose, or the cloth has stretched with the hoop's screw at its current position.",
            "symptom": "The Aida is slipping out of the hoop as you stitch"
          }
        ],
        "heading": "Common first-sampler troubles"
      }
    }
  ]
